metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #87
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of SpecterðŸ‘»pixelâ¬›latteâ˜•, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agentsâ€”the small moving circlesâ€”that get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.

metadata.name: Polar Grid #629
metadata.description:
Polar Grid is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022.

This is a study of color, motion, and composition, and an homage to cinema as an artform. Colorful shapes overlap and pulse in a ever repeating dance. An abstracted movie experience. Each color palette in the series (except one) is inspired by a different film director (if you want a real challenge, see how many you can guess without looking at the feature names).

The palettes were extracted from movie stills or movie posters and fine tuned by hand. As often, I have to thank independent tool makers for their indirect help. My gratitude goes to David Aerne for FarbVÃ©lo and Fabrizio Bianchi for Coolors.

The code for Polar Grid is based on early iterations of what ultimately became my carat series. Both projects come from the same fascination for color as a system, even though I used a different approach here. You could call this a carat prequel.

The animation is done using a technique called polar noise. This makes it so the motion of all elements ends up repeating in the same amount of time. This is useful for generating motion that loops perfectly while still appearing organic. In this particular case, the animation repeats every Ï€ Ã— 100 seconds.

A challenge in building any generative system is to find the right balance between coherence and variety. I designed the system with the large edition size in mind. During development I generated hundreds of iterations and tweaked my code to make sure that every iteration is truly unique and fits the overall aesthetic of the collection.

I truly hope you will enjoy your own little abstract movie.

â€” RaphaÃ«l de Courville


Released: July 6th 2022

Medium: p5.js, html canvas, css

Reference: sk220621


**About the artist**

RaphaÃ«l de Courville is a generative artist, streamer, and educator. His artistic work is an exploration of generative systems, patterns, interactivity, and time. Born in Paris, he lives and works in Berlin.

- Press F to hide/show the browser UI

metadata.name: lightscapes//linescapes//darkscapes #135
metadata.description:
A landscape made of monochromatic rows arranged by color to create an illusion of depth.

Each token comes with some fixed constraints, some constantly changing elements, and 3 possible styles.

The lightscape mode creates the most natural view, while the darkscape mode reveals the skeleton of the image. The linescape mode blends the two and looks a bit more like an illustration.

CONTROLS:
- click/tap on the image to regenerate and cycle through the different styles
- press 's' to download a png at the current resolution

Hope you like it,
Cino

In this one, the cells head for absolute chaos, before finally disappearing.

- Cells absorb each other

metadata.name: Excavation #88
metadata.description:
"Excavation" reconstructs the digital screen as a thickened, palimpsestuous ground. Elements are uncovered through an archaeological survey of this ground, while others remain buried beneath layers of digital sediment.

Coded in p5.js.

metadata.name: TENDER Pass #596
metadata.description:
Tender is a curatorial platform and community that helps bring incredible works of generative art to discerning collectors.

Holding a TENDER Pass enables enriched benefits and experiences within the Tender ecosystem. Passholders expand their access to unique collaborations with extraordinary artists, indispensable collector tools, curatorial experiences, artwork insights, fine art prints, a thriving community, and more.

Tender is committed to stewarding the growth of generative art and amplifying the voices of artists and collectors across the entire lifecycle: from creation to collection to curation, and back again. Every Pass minted and resold directly enables Tender to continue creating the platform and experiences that serve this mission.

â€”â€”

TENDER Pass features unique artwork by punevyr. While all Passes are special, a small number of randomly generated, rarified tokens will come with boosted benefits. If you have a piece with a dark background of any kind, you likely possess one of the following:

Bonus Pass
TENDER Passes with the special Bonus trait get 1 guaranteed reserve spot on all TENDER x Collab projects

Grail Pass
TENDER Passes with the special Grail trait get 2 free mints on all TENDER x Collab projects


New Passholders may access our Discord server thatâ€™s linked from our website.
For TENDER Pass benefits and up-to-date details, please visit tender.art/pass

---

TENDER x punevyr

metadata.name: StairWaves #156
metadata.description:
StairWaves is a generative collection imagining abstract stairs built in a wavy nature, with shadows being a key theme. While some waves are quite turbulent, others are just flat.

All shapes in the artwork are built using the same core logic applied in different ways. The method used to draw the waves is also used to draw the shadows, as well as the subtle textures on the surface of the waves. This homogeneous approach ensures a consistent and flowy feel to the final output.

StairWaves is coded entirely in p5.js. 

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)

metadata.name: Motherboard deluxe #2
metadata.description:
A random little mesh checkerboard assembled in an organised mess, with certain shapes each representing different musical notes.

- CLICK a random square or rectangle shape to trigger their respective playback.
- HOLD DOWN and drag to explore further.

Having different grid sizes generated, each cell is populated by a various selection of shapes.
The squares and rectangles however are the ones to pay extra attention to. Each of them represent single or multiple notes. The more cells that the shape covers, the more notes are attached to it. A rectangle will trigger 2 attacks, a large square that covers 4 cells will trigger 4 attacks and so on. Due to randomisation, one or several shapes may intersect each other, possibly resulting in a series of symbols and an even more extensive chord hit.

Holding down your pointer vill invoke a flashlight that follows your every move. By dragging the plane while having the pointer held down, each square that you pass over will be triggered.

As a feature youâ€™re able to collect 2 different types of instruments.
The well familiar Harmonised 3-Osc Pad from before, but this time around a semi-muted Harpolodic String Synth has additionally been brought on as a guest. Both instruments are evenly distributed amongst the editions.

Each edition also has its own set structure of ordered notes and scales, hence each one might have a different sound composition.

Whatâ€™s more is random sizes, positions and colors as well as a diversity of flashlights, ambient lightings and background gradients.

Thereâ€™s a 25% chance of getting a colored flashlight. Itâ€™s 33% less likely that you get a light background theme. Thereâ€™s a 9% chance of getting a colored lighting theme. And approximately 1.6% of you will get the whole palette in sepia.

As before, each series of shapes get their total composition calculated down to a single percentage that indicates its uniqueness.

@computeremotions - 2022-07-15

metadata.name: Interconnected #35
Stripped Down V2 #87
metadata.description:
The last series in the journey of geometric shapes.
This was the initial algorithm behind "Zometric" and "Delight". Starting with the basic grid, rectangles and parallel lines. I used the black color for the composition with a pastel palette for the background. hope you enjoy it.
